<section xml:id="sec-exploring-data">
  <title>Exploring Data</title>
  
  <introduction>
    <p>
      This topic builds your curiosity and practical habits for exploring new datasets. You'll learn quick, reliable ways to <q>get the lay of the land</q> so you don't get surprised later in analysis. We focus on pivot tables, graphs, and summary statistics to spot patterns, compare groups, and flag anomalies.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <objectives>
    <introduction>
      <p>By the end of this topic you will be able to:</p>
    </introduction>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>Construct basic pivot tables to summarise categorical and numeric variables (counts, proportions, means).</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Produce and interpret core summaries and simple graphs (e.g., histograms, boxplots, bar charts) to describe distributions and compare groups.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Detect patterns, trends, and anomalies (e.g., outliers, missingness, group differences) and explain why they matter for further analysis.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Formulate follow-up questions and next steps (a short EDA plan) that justify what you would explore next and why.</p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-exploring-tasks">
    <title>Your Tasks</title>
    <p>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>Watch the video introducing pivot tables, and complete the two STACK quizzes on pivot tables.</p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>Participate in the forum: post one graph and one summary from the MICS Kenya data and respond to two peers.</p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>Conduct a mini-EDA case study using pivot tables and plots, and submit a small interpretation.</p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </subsection>

